I‚Äôm so excited to share that our preprint on self-supervised learning for BGCs is released!

I had the best internship experience at MSR and learned so much about deep learning. I feel so lucky to have been part of an amazing and encouraging team with Kevin, Nick, Ava, & Lorin!üôåüèª https://t.co/eyKdjlLBum
Impressively, Carolina had never done deep learning before her internship last summer! She's deservedly going to Stanford in the Fall as an NSF graduate research fellow.

After self-supervised training, we can use the model's uncertainty when reconstructing sequences of domains in bacterial genomes to detect BGCs, or just stick a MASK to the beginning of BGCs and use its prediction to predict product classes.
We then tacked a token representing the product class to the beginning of each BGC sequence and trained a CNN to reconstruct the sequence after we corrupted it.

BGCs do cool chemistry to make natural products that could be useful as therapeutics, but they're hard to discover / express / characterize. 

We started with a set of about 100k annotated BGCs and represented them as sequences of pfam domains.
